journey and how you ended up in, not just

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:52.140
the industry, but in one of the most coveted
and storied traditions in all of history.

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:53.600
&gt;&gt;Mark: Ooops.

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:54.600
Ah.

00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:56.030
I've been drawing all my life.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:58.759
You know, ever since I was three.

00:01:58.759 --> 00:02:03.090
My dad worked in Lenwood, California.

00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:07.020
He was a schoolteacher and counselor and dean
of the high school there.

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:09.789
And computers were just coming out.

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:15.660
So he would bring home the reams of the white
and green computer paper.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:21.840
'Cause they would only print whatever numbers
on one side, so he'd bring home stacks of

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:23.950
this stuff for me.

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:26.420
That was just folded, you know.

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:27.420
Reams of it.

00:02:27.420 --> 00:02:32.060
And I would just draw on it and draw on the
opposite side.

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:37.360
So I've been drawing all my life and did high
school and stuff.

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:38.690
I'm not ambitious.

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:40.670
I didn't have any aspirations to do anything.

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:43.330
I didn't know what I was gonna do after high
school.

00:02:43.330 --> 00:02:44.330
I just drew.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:46.930
I was gonna be a Marine after high School.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:49.050
All my friends were goin' in the armed services.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:50.920
My best friend's in the Navy.

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:53.090
I have other friends who were in the Marines.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:55.620
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: That explains some of the
sword fighting.

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:56.620
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yes.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:58.069
Well I've been doing martial arts all my life.

00:02:58.069 --> 00:03:00.620
And sword fighting.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:06.290
And so out of high school, I didn't take any
college prep classes or nothin'.

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:08.880
So high school ends, and I'm all "What do
I do now?"

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:10.230
So I'm talking to a Marine Recruiter.

00:03:10.230 --> 00:03:14.550
I'm not ready to go right into the Marines
right then and there.

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:17.849
So I'm all "Ahh, well, City College I guess."

00:03:17.849 --> 00:03:21.500
So I went to City College and that's where
I got my first formal training as an artist

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:25.490
and life drawing, perspective, and just drawing.

00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:28.099
Which was more like rendering.

00:03:28.099 --> 00:03:30.180
You know, crosshatching.

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:32.790
And I did two years of City College.

00:03:32.790 --> 00:03:35.830
And this was all in Santa Barbara.

00:03:35.830 --> 00:03:41.760
And one class, one semester this guy was offering
this animation course.

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:44.420
And I'd been into Japanese animation my whole
life.

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:48.010
You know, Kimba the White Lion, Speed Racer,
Star Blazers, RoboTech.

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:49.840
You know all this stuff.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:54.500
Akira had come out when I was graduating high
school and I was just "Whoa, this is amazing!"

00:03:54.500 --> 00:04:00.189
So I'm doing animation class and I'm doing
my own kind of anime type stuff that's just

00:04:00.189 --> 00:04:01.189
ultraviolent.

00:04:01.189 --> 00:04:02.189
You know.

00:04:02.189 --> 00:04:03.200
Fun thing.

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:08.720
And he tells me, the instructor tells me about
Cal Arts, which is up in Valencia.

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:10.150
California Institute of the Arts.

00:04:10.150 --> 00:04:14.489
And I'm all, "You can actually do this for
a living?

00:04:14.489 --> 00:04:15.489
Wow.

00:04:15.489 --> 00:04:16.489
I better apply."

00:04:16.489 --> 00:04:22.950
So me and my brother applied at Cal Arts and
we got in and I remember calling my recruiter

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:26.080
the Marine Recruiter and saying "Sorry man,
I'm goin' to art school."

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:29.680
So, he was kind of upset.

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.640
[laughter]
So I did four years of Cal Arts and got my

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:34.450
degree in film.

00:04:34.450 --> 00:04:35.450
Whoopee.

00:04:35.450 --> 00:04:37.990
And got out and starved for a year.

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:39.290
&gt;&gt;Male presenter: Yeah.

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:41.080
What was starving like for you?

00:04:41.080 --> 00:04:42.080
How did that

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:43.080
&gt;&gt;Mark: oh, it was fun.

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:46.300
It was livin' off a credit card and eating
potato chips and hot dogs.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:47.300
That's it.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:50.900
That was the cheapest food I could find that
was kinda substantial.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:52.330
I couldn't do ramen every day.

00:04:52.330 --> 00:04:55.350
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Even though you had a predisposition
for Japanese culture.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:57.600
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yes, yes.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.970
But not a predisposition for Japanese food.

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:00.970
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:05:00.970 --> 00:05:01.970
Yeah.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:03.920
&gt;&gt;Mark: I like things that are cooked.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:10.550
So, all my friends got jobs in the animation
industry and I was the only one who didn't.

00:05:10.550 --> 00:05:13.050
I went to the Disney internship right out
of school.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:16.050
I was the only one out of five who didn't
get fired because I rocked the boat.

00:05:16.050 --> 00:05:17.480
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: I read about that.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:19.280
And I'm kind of curious.

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:21.450
I mean, like, how did you rock the boat?

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:22.800
I mean, were you a punk?

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:23.800
Or were you

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:24.800
&gt;&gt;Mark: They.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:25.800
No.

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:26.800
No.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:27.800
I was just being me.

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:28.800
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Was it the hot dogs?

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:29.800
&gt;&gt;Mark: It was the hot dogs.

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:32.680
I was just me, and at the end of the internship
they want you to kind of do a presentation,

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:33.680
right?

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:35.810
That this is what I wanna do.

00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:36.810
And they were really looking.

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:37.850
I mean this was the hype.

00:05:37.850 --> 00:05:40.220
They were animating Lion King when I was there.

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:46.070
And they were rolling out Pocahontas and Hunchback
of Notre Dame and all these things were just

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:50.320
comin' off of Beauty and the Beast.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.620
So it's startin' to go up.

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:55.410
And DreamWorks is just being created at this
time.

00:05:55.410 --> 00:05:58.100
So this was like Golden Age of animation.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:00.600
So they wanted animators 'cause they didn't
have enough.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:01.710
And I could animate.

00:06:01.710 --> 00:06:05.280
But what I was really falling in love with
was story boarding.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:12.370
So I was the only one out of five interns
who presented two presentations.

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:16.300
And because I presented two presentations,
one in animation and one on story, they don't

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:19.530
like to make a decision at Disney.

00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:21.250
And that's rockin' the boat.

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:23.220
So they came in and looked at it.

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:26.430
And I thought you know, you guys pick.

00:06:26.430 --> 00:06:27.430
Either or.

00:06:27.430 --> 00:06:28.430
I'm happy.

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:29.430
But they couldn't.

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:31.840
And that just totally threw them and so I
was the only one who didn't get hired.

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:33.410
And then I was blacklisted at Disney.

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:34.410
And they wouldn't hire me.

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:36.680
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: I mean it sounds like, I
mean blacklisted seems like you would have

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:39.460
