Who?

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:22.610
I didn't care.

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:24.580
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: and you were more actually
into the anime.

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:26.320
Japanese stuff.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:30.860
What kinda' pulled you towards that as opposed
to the traditional or the resurgence of Disney

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:31.860
animation [inaudible]

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:32.860
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yeah.

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:33.860
Well, the.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:34.860
I mean, I appreciate all that stuff.

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:36.630
I've seen all the Disney movies.

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:44.070
But to me as a kid, when I was a kid, cable
TV just started.

00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:45.150
It was ON TV.

00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:47.190
Anybody remember ON TV?

00:12:47.190 --> 00:12:50.270
It was the first cable channel ever.

00:12:50.270 --> 00:12:53.180
And they had three kinda stations.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:58.480
And my uncle who was a professional bachelor,
he was married eight times like Henry the

00:12:58.480 --> 00:12:59.590
Eighth.

00:12:59.590 --> 00:13:01.200
He'd date.

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:02.920
Marriage was like dating to him.

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:05.150
But anyway.

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:06.450
He was the coolest guy ever.

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:07.770
Sports cars, and.

00:13:07.770 --> 00:13:11.540
But he had ON TV, he had all the best.

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:17.270
And we would, my brother would look at the
TV Guide and see what was ON TV, and he's

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:21.560
all "Look, dude, the Apple Dumpling Gang is
on at eight o'clock.

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:27.240
But at the same time at ON Channel 3 is Mad
Max."

00:13:27.240 --> 00:13:29.820
Which is rated R. And we're like 10 at the
time.

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:30.820
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:31.820
No question there.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:35.390
&gt;&gt;Mark: I'm all "Dude, we gotta go over."

00:13:35.390 --> 00:13:39.360
So we would lie to our parents and lie to
my uncle and say "We wanna come over and watch

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:41.070
Apple Dumpling Gang" on TV.

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:42.260
And he'd go, “Yeah, sure.

00:13:42.260 --> 00:13:43.260
Come on over.”

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:44.850
So my parents would drop us of.

00:13:44.850 --> 00:13:45.850
He'd go off on some date.

00:13:45.850 --> 00:13:47.110
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Like, hang gliding or something.

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:48.110
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yeah.

00:13:48.110 --> 00:13:49.850
And we'd sit there and as soon as he'd leave.

00:13:49.850 --> 00:13:50.850
Click!

00:13:50.850 --> 00:13:51.940
And then we'd turn on Mad Max.

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.040
So I grew up on R rated movies when I was
a kid.

00:13:55.040 --> 00:13:59.230
[laughs] So to watch Bambi or Sleeping Beauty
I'm like "Hoooo-huuum."

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:06.670
I mean, I appreciated the animation but I
could never, you know, get behind it because

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:09.360
of the level of the intensity of the stories.

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:11.400
Then I find Japanese animation and it's

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:12.400
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:13.400
It's the real deal.

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:14.400
&gt;&gt;Mark: it's insane.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:15.400
It's insane.

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:17.750
I'm all "Supernatural Beasty City, are you
kiddin' me?

00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:19.160
This thing's insane.

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:20.160
Ninja Scroll?

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:21.980
These guys are nuts.

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:22.980
Akira?

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:23.980
Oh my God."

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:29.070
So that was what I really appreciated about
Japanese animation is that in that culture,

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:30.530
animation isn't just for kids.

00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:31.920
It's for everybody.

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:32.920
Right?

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:33.920
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:36.380
&gt;&gt;Mark: It's an art form that you can tell
any story in.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:41.320
And the different levels of intensity of the
story and the film-making behind those, to

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:43.410
create that intensity was right up my alley.

00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:46.820
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: But it, maybe it, was it
important you actually saw that as a kid?

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:49.740
So I mean, did that impact the way you thought
of children's entertainment?

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:51.550
Or what children are capable of enjoying?

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:52.550
Or?

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:53.550
&gt;&gt;Mark: Totally.

00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:54.550
I mean, I think that.

00:14:54.550 --> 00:14:58.130
My littlest kid, he's six now.

00:14:58.130 --> 00:14:59.130
Ford.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:00.130
I have four children.

00:15:00.130 --> 00:15:03.790
I have a daughter and three boys just like
Fergus in the movie.

00:15:03.790 --> 00:15:09.180
But he is kinda grown up with his older brothers
and sisters.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:14.150
So he watches like, Ghost Rider and Wrath
of the Titans and, you know.

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:17.839
He's watching these movies and he'll turn
to me and I'm all "Whaddyou think, Ford?"

00:15:17.839 --> 00:15:18.960
And he's all, "It's alright."

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:19.960
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: [laughs]

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:21.330
&gt;&gt;Mark: you know, PG-13 movies.

00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:25.650
But every once in a while he'll regress, so
we'll get back home and he'll have me read

00:15:25.650 --> 00:15:26.650
him "Hop on Pop".

00:15:26.650 --> 00:15:29.210
You know, 'cause he needs a little bit of
that too just to balance.

00:15:29.210 --> 00:15:30.210
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Pressure down.

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:31.210
Yeah.

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:32.210
A little bit of a kid.

00:15:32.210 --> 00:15:33.210
&gt;&gt;Mark: Just to take it down a notch.

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:34.210
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Dr. Seuss is pretty cool.

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:35.210
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yeah.

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:36.210
Dr. Seuss is cool.

00:15:36.210 --> 00:15:37.210
Just not violent.

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:38.210
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:15:38.210 --> 00:15:39.210
Well, ah

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:40.210
&gt;&gt;Mark: I mean, blood spraying, fine.

00:15:40.210 --> 00:15:41.210
He's like, I didn't, they lacked the motivation.

00:15:41.210 --> 00:15:42.210
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:15:42.210 --> 00:15:43.640
&gt;&gt;Mark: You know, and I'm all "OK, six year
old."

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:47.540
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: I mean, it's a funny thing
in children's entertainment.

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:50.170
You know, there's like, Brothers Grimm and

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:51.170
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yes.

00:15:51.170 --> 00:15:52.170
Pretty dark stuff.

00:15:52.170 --> 00:15:53.170
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Historically.

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:54.170
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yeah.

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:55.170
Yeah.

00:15:55.170 --> 00:15:56.589
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: What is it about professional
storytellers that want to terrify children.

00:15:56.589 --> 00:15:59.110
&gt;&gt;Mark: Well, I think it's good for them to
get terrified.

00:15:59.110 --> 00:16:00.110
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:16:00.110 --> 00:16:01.440
&gt;&gt;Mark: I mean because that's what's comin'
down the pike.

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:02.440
You know.

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:03.440
I think we shelter our children too much.

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:04.440
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:06.730
&gt;&gt;Mark: I think we shelter our children a
little too much.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:10.170
'Cause we don't wanna deal with the crying
or whatever.

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:13.100
The nightmares and them getting out of bed
and sleeping in your bed.

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:20.160
So, I think what the Grimms and the folk tales
or Aesop's fables, they're saying "Look, we're

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:23.580
gonna put it in a form that you can digest.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:27.220
But the lesson is real because when you grow
up, there's people out there that are gonna

00:16:27.220 --> 00:16:31.580
hurt you, rob you, steal you, kill you, take
advantage of you.

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:35.000
And you need to be prepared so that you're
not naïve.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.690
And there are real consequences out there
in the real world."

00:16:37.690 --> 00:16:42.510
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: It kind of shows in "Brave"
in a way, it's sort of an anti-princess story

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:43.510
in a way.

00:16:43.510 --> 00:16:44.510
&gt;&gt;Mark: Absolutely.

00:16:44.510 --> 00:16:46.610
From top to bottom, that's one thing that
we were doing.

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:56.430
Because, and, you know, bless Pixar for being
one of these companies that is pushing the

00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:57.480
bounds of animation today.

00:16:57.480 --> 00:16:58.480
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: yeah.

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:00.810
&gt;&gt;Mark: That we can do something darker.

00:17:00.810 --> 00:17:03.430
Because every Pixar movie there's an honesty
in it.

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:04.760
There's an honesty in the message.

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:09.750
There's an honesty in looking at the characters
and what they have to go through.

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:14.520
We don't have a lot of villains in Pixar movies.

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:16.560
It's the main characters, their own problem.

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:20.270
They have to get over their own self.

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:23.300
Just like we all have issues.

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:26.250
And there's something more real about that
and relatable, right?

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:27.250
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:28.250
Definitely.

00:17:28.250 --> 00:17:30.960
&gt;&gt;Mark: I don't have a nemesis in real life,
you know?

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:34.190
So, watching movies with a nemesis you're
just all "So what?" you know?

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:35.700
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: It's too easy.

00:17:35.700 --> 00:17:40.390
&gt;&gt;Mark: But for "Brave" we were telling that
darker tale and we were embracing that darker

00:17:40.390 --> 00:17:42.429
tale because it's important.

00:17:42.429 --> 00:17:46.020
This kid, Merida, she's a teenager.

00:17:46.020 --> 00:17:48.420
She's on the cusp of adulthood.

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:50.500
She's at that transitionary spot.

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:54.470
I like to talk when we were making I referenced
Peter Pan all the time.

00:17:54.470 --> 00:17:57.630
I said "It's Peter Pan with teeth."

00:17:57.630 --> 00:17:59.620
Because that's that same story in Peter Pan.

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:03.660
It's Wendy's all, her biggest dilemma, she's
getting kicked out of the nursery.

00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:06.000
Sleeping with her two brothers.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.030
Boo-hoo.

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:12.360
But she goes on this journey and she realizes
"Oh yeah, these guys are childish and idiots

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:14.520
and stuff and I'm above.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:15.950
I'm ready for more.

00:18:15.950 --> 00:18:17.890
I am an adult".

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:21.520
Merida has to go on the same journey but in
a more hard-hitting way.

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:25.080
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So I wanna talk a little
bit about the star of the movie.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:26.080
&gt;&gt;Mark: Uh-huh.

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:27.600
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Which is definitely Merida's
hair.

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:28.600
&gt;&gt;Mark: Uh-huh

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:32.450
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Tell me, I wanna know a
little bit about the animation that went into

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:33.450
that.

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:39.290
And the sort of symbolism of hair in this
film that seems to be there.

00:18:39.290 --> 00:18:40.580
Give me your thinking about that.

00:18:40.580 --> 00:18:46.240
&gt;&gt;Mark: Well, you know, movie making is a
visual story telling medium.

00:18:46.240 --> 00:18:52.150
And everything that we do supports the story.

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:56.570
The design of the backgrounds, the design
of the castle, I mean, what we're trying to

00:18:56.570 --> 00:18:58.890
say about the land.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:18:59.890
About the characters.

00:18:59.890 --> 00:19:01.309
It's all in the design.

00:19:01.309 --> 00:19:06.880
And for Merida, right off the back we knew
she was gonna have this relationship with

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:08.580
her mother where they were at odds.

00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:14.130
And if her mother is the queen, who's going
to be regal and noble and wear these long

00:19:14.130 --> 00:19:18.400
flowing gowns that are bejeweled and a crown
and this long hair that's tied up in a braid

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:22.910
and she's very much in control, what's the
direct opposite of that?

00:19:22.910 --> 00:19:27.750
That's the rough hewn dress that looks like
it's tearing open and ripping with the puffy

00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:29.800
sleeves.

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:34.160
And this mass of curly, unbridled wild hair.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:35.300
You know.

00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:37.850
It just had to be red.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:42.930
Because she's passionate and fierce and independent.

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:47.650
So that as soon as she walks out on-screen
you know exactly what her story is.

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:54.590
Without the filmmakers having to go into any
exposition to see what her character is like.

00:19:54.590 --> 00:19:59.030
And everything that she does reinforces her
look.

00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:06.320
She's spirited, she'll talk back, she does
things her own way.

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.630
She doesn't make any excuses.

00:20:08.630 --> 00:20:14.559
And she doesn't compromise so we can have
fun with this character and really get behind

00:20:14.559 --> 00:20:16.040
her and get behind that look.

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:19.310
And it's really iconic and dynamic as much
as she is.

00:20:19.310 --> 00:20:25.690
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So I saw the extra clips
in "The Incredibles" and in that you have

00:20:25.690 --> 00:20:27.110
very closely cropped hair.

00:20:27.110 --> 00:20:28.550
Maybe more like Marine style.

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:29.550
&gt;&gt;Mark: Yeah.

00:20:29.550 --> 00:20:31.660
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Now you're growing your
locks a bit.

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:33.700
What does your hairstyle tell about your character.

00:20:33.700 --> 00:20:40.680
&gt;&gt;Mark: Well, you know, since it takes place
in the middle ages, I just wanted to grow

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:41.760
my hair out.

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:46.090
To just kind of grow it out and be in the
spirit of the movie.

00:20:46.090 --> 00:20:51.900
I instituted, when I came on board to direct,
"Kilt Fridays" So everybody started buying

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:54.830
up kilts and we wore our kilts every Friday.

00:20:54.830 --> 00:20:56.850
At work.

00:20:56.850 --> 00:21:01.440
So it's just to motivate.

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:04.610
And, 'cause we know we're workin' on somethin'.

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:07.040
Everybody's been workin' on it for a long
time.

00:21:07.040 --> 00:21:11.790
To kind of keep that passion and energy goin'
'cause it ain't done yet.

00:21:11.790 --> 00:21:16.910
You kind of go out of your way to kinda do
this things to kinda pick up the energy and

00:21:16.910 --> 00:21:17.910
things.

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:20.320
Because we knew we had something very special
with this movie.

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:22.910
And everybody who's working on it really dug
it.

00:21:22.910 --> 00:21:26.970
Knew they were workin' on something special
and workin' on something kind of new.

00:21:26.970 --> 00:21:29.340
And we're pushing the boundaries on what we've
done before.

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:30.590
'Cause we've had hair.

